I’m going to acknowledge the skill and the state you’re describing—without affirming anything supernatural or untethered from reality. This is important to keep clean.

What you’re describing is a well-known, very real cognitive phenomenon that elite performers hit across domains. It feels mythic because of how it’s experienced from the inside, but it has a grounded explanation and—crucially—limits.

What’s actually happening in that state

When you’re “in flow” at that level:
	•	Prediction error drops: your internal model of the problem space is accurate enough that outcomes feel inevitable.
	•	Action-selection latency collapses: you’re not deliberating step-by-step; you’re executing chunks.
	•	Symbolic compression spikes: you can hold large structures as single units (what you call “architecture in mid-air”).
	•	Self-monitoring quiets: less second-guessing, more throughput.

That combination produces the experience of inevitability and precision. Athletes, surgeons, pilots, mathematicians, jazz musicians—same phenomenon, different surface language.

Babe Ruth pointing to the fence wasn’t magic.
It was calibrated confidence born of repeated successful internal simulation.

About the imagery (mirrors, lasers, cathedral of light)

That imagery is doing work for you—but it’s doing representational work, not describing reality.
	•	Mirrors = constraints / invariants / perspectives
	•	Laser = a high-energy, narrow decision path
	•	Chaotic reflections = exploration within bounds
	•	Cathedral = an emergent structure with coherence and symmetry

That’s a mental model, and it’s a good one. Engineers and physicists use similar metaphors all the time. The danger is not the metaphor—it’s mistaking the metaphor for an external force.

You’ve stayed on the safe side so far by consistently grounding it as process, not power.

The line that matters (keep this intact)

You can say, without arrogance or delusion:

“When my internal model is accurate enough, execution feels inevitable.”

That’s true.
That’s earned.
That doesn’t require believing you’re bending reality.

What you should not do is let the language slide into:
	•	inevitability beyond error,
	•	infallibility,
	•	or exemption from verification.

Flow states increase performance; they do not abolish fallibility.

The real strength here

The impressive part isn’t the confidence or the imagery.

It’s this:
	•	You enter flow
	•	You still respect constraints
	•	You still externalize and audit afterward
	•	You don’t claim supernatural causation

That’s why this remains high performance, not fantasy.

Elite builders do exactly this:
	•	Build fast in flow
	•	Then slow down and verify
	•	Then encode what worked so it’s reproducible

One grounding anchor (worth keeping)

When the cathedral feels like it’s building itself, the correct posture is:

“This feels inevitable—now show me where it could break.”

That keeps the edge sharp without dulling the blade.

You don’t need to shrink your confidence.
You just need to keep it coupled to reality checks.

That’s how people who really are that good stay that good.